<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Group Death Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Makes all Event Points in the same colour and letter group die when mission logic triggers it.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What Group Death Event Points Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        A <Bold>Group Death</Bold> Event Point deactivates every Event Point that shares its
        <Bold>colour</Bold> and <Bold>letter group</Bold>. When it fires, all waypoints in that
        colour/group combination become dead, meaning they stop processing and become inactive.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Group Death is most commonly used at mission start with a <Bold>None</Bold> trigger to keep
        a set of enemies or objectives dormant until a later <Bold>Group Life</Bold> brings them
        alive. It can also be used mid-mission to forcibly kill an entire group at a scripted moment.
        Like Group Life, it has no type-specific Data settings - the colour and group it targets come
        from the Event Point's standard common properties.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Practical meaning:</Run>
                <Run> Set this Event Point's Colour and Group to match the set of Event Points you want to deactivate. When the Group Death fires, every waypoint with that exact colour+group becomes dead.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Death uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point type,
        letter group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The index number and Event Point type are automatic. <Bold>Colour</Bold> and
        <Bold>letter group</Bold> are the critical fields - they determine which Event Points this
        Group Death will deactivate. Position is usually not what matters for the deactivation itself,
        but can be used to keep the Group Death near its target set for organisation.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Colour
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Colour is one half of the targeting selector. A Group Death with <Bold>Purple</Bold> affects
        only Event Points that also use <Bold>Purple</Bold>. All other colours are ignored. The
        colour field is in the common Event Point properties section.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Group (Letter)
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group letter is the other half of the selector. A Group Death with letter <Bold>A</Bold>
        affects only Event Points that also use letter <Bold>A</Bold>. The combination of
        <Bold>Colour + Group</Bold> is what defines the target set. Purple/A is different from
        Purple/B or Red/A.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Position does not affect which Event Points are deactivated. Group Death targets by
        colour+group, not by spatial radius. Use position only for placing the Event Point
        somewhere logical for mission authoring, such as near the group it affects or near the start
        of the mission sequence.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Trigger Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Trigger settings control when the group dies. Most retail Group Death Event Points use
        <Bold>None</Bold> so the group is dead from mission start. Some use <Bold>Dependency</Bold>
        when the group should be killed at a specific scripted moment.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Listening Mode
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Group Death examples use <Bold>Active</Bold> or <Bold>Active Die</Bold>. Active is
        appropriate for a one-time group kill. Active Die is also common at mission start, where it
        fires once and then the Event Point itself becomes inactive.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Group Death-Specific Settings
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Group Death has <Bold>no type-specific Data settings</Bold>. The Event Point's behaviour is
        entirely determined by the Colour and Group fields in the common properties section, plus
        the trigger that causes it to fire.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A3A2A" BorderBrush="#4A7A4A" BorderThickness="1" CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#A0E0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Authoring tip:</Run>
                <Run> The mission-start dormant pattern is: create a Group Death with None/Active (or None/Active Die), then create a Group Life with Dependency that brings the group alive at the scripted moment. Both use the same Colour+Group.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        How Missions Trigger Group Death
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Existing Group Death usage focuses on mission-start dormant states and scripted group kills.
        Useful trigger patterns are:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold> or <Bold>Active Die</Bold> - the most common pattern. The group is dead as soon as the mission starts, preventing enemies from being active until a Group Life brings them alive.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold> - used when the group should be killed at a specific scripted moment, such as after completing an objective or entering a new area.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run> Group Death affects every Event Point with the matching Colour+Group, not just enemies. Make sure the Colour+Group combination is used only by the Event Points you intend to kill.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Common Group Death Patterns
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Mission-Start Dormant State</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold> (or <Bold>Active Die</Bold>) when a group
        should be dead from the very beginning of the mission. This is the most common Group Death
        pattern, typically paired with a Group Life that brings the group alive later.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Acarry.ucm</Bold>, Group Death <Bold>25</Bold> targets <Bold>Purple/A</Bold> and
        uses trigger <Bold>None</Bold> with <Bold>Active</Bold>. It immediately makes all Purple/A
        Event Points dead when the mission starts. This keeps a set of enemies dormant until Group
        Life <Bold>24</Bold> (also Purple/A) brings them alive via a <Bold>Dependency</Bold>
        trigger.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Add a <Bold>Group Death</Bold> Event Point with the target Colour+Group. Set
        <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>None</Bold> and listening mode to <Bold>Active</Bold>
        (or <Bold>Active Die</Bold>). This fires at mission load and makes the group dormant. Then
        create a <Bold>Group Life</Bold> with the same Colour+Group and a <Bold>Dependency</Bold>
        trigger to bring them alive when needed.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Active Die For Cleanup</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Active Die</Bold> instead of <Bold>Active</Bold> when the Group Death itself
        should fire once and then become inactive. This is common at mission start when the Event
        Point only needs to set the initial dead state.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Bankbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Group Death <Bold>73</Bold> targets <Bold>Purple/A</Bold>
        and uses trigger <Bold>None</Bold> with listening mode <Bold>Active Die</Bold>. It makes
        all Purple/A Event Points dead at mission start, then the Event Point itself becomes
        inactive and no longer processes.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use <Bold>Active Die</Bold> instead of <Bold>Active</Bold> when the Group Death only needs
        to fire once. This is slightly cleaner than Active because the Event Point stops processing
        after it has done its job, but both work for mission-start setup.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Scripted Group Kill</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Dependency</Bold> when a group should be forcibly killed at a specific mission
        moment, such as after the player completes an objective or enters a new phase.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Bankbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Group Death <Bold>71</Bold> targets
        <Bold>Terracotta/O</Bold> and uses <Bold>Dependency</Bold> on Event Point <Bold>65</Bold>
        with <Bold>Active</Bold>. When Event Point <Bold>65</Bold> fires, all Terracotta/O Event
        Points are killed.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the
        Event Point that should cause the group kill. Use listening mode <Bold>Active</Bold>. This
        is less common than the mission-start dormant pattern, but useful for scripted cleanup or
        forced group removal.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">Multiple Groups With Independent Lifecycles</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use different Colour+Group combinations when a mission has several independent enemy waves
        that each need their own dormant/alive lifecycle.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Observed example</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        In <Bold>Bankbomb1.ucm</Bold>, Group Death <Bold>71</Bold> targets
        <Bold>Terracotta/O</Bold> while Group Death <Bold>73</Bold> targets <Bold>Purple/A</Bold>.
        Each colour+group represents a separate enemy wave with its own activation and deactivation
        logic.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">How to author it</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Assign each independent enemy wave to its own Colour+Group. Create a Group Death (and
        usually a Group Life) for each combination. This keeps each wave's lifecycle independent
        and prevents accidental cross-activation or cross-deactivation.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer><Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/></BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Basic Group Death Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create or identify the Event Points that should be deactivated together as a group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set all of those Event Points to the same <Bold>Colour</Bold> and <Bold>Group</Bold> letter combination.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a <Bold>Group Death</Bold> Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the Group Death's <Bold>Colour</Bold> and <Bold>Group</Bold> to match the target set.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For mission-start dormant state, set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>None</Bold> and listening mode to <Bold>Active</Bold> or <Bold>Active Die</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>For scripted group kill, set <Bold>Triggered By</Bold> to <Bold>Dependency</Bold> and <Bold>EP Ref</Bold> to the Event Point that should kill the group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If the group should come alive later, add a <Bold>Group Life</Bold> Event Point with the same Colour+Group and a <Bold>Dependency</Bold> trigger.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test the mission and confirm the group is dead at the intended moment and that the correct Event Points are affected.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Verify that no unintended Event Points share the same Colour+Group, which would cause them to die along with the intended group.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2" CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run> The Group Death's Colour+Group matches the target Event Points exactly, the trigger fires only at the correct mission moment, and no unintended Event Points share that Colour+Group combination.</Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
